The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in Asiaâ€™s local bonds and
currencies today. Yields and exchange rates are from the
previous trading session unless stated otherwise.  Financial markets in Japan, South Korea and China are
closed today for public holidays.  Malaysia: The government is scheduled to auction Islamic
bonds maturing in 2013 this month. It may disclose the amount
and date of the offering today. It last issued similar debt of
that maturity in January at an average yield of 3.29 percent.  The yield on the 3.835 percent bond due August 2015 was
3.30 percent. The ringgit was at 3.0890.  Singapore: Consumer prices in August rose 3.3 percent from
a year earlier the Department of Statistics will say today,
according to a Bloomberg News survey, after a 3.1 percent gain
in July.  The yield on the 3.25 percent debt due September 2020 was
2.06 percent. The Singapore dollar was at S$1.3263.  Taiwan: The government will say today industrial production
rose 21.6 percent in August from a year earlier, according to a
Bloomberg survey of economists, after having increased 20.7
percent in July. The jobless rate fell to 5.1 percent, the
lowest level in 20 months, according to a separate survey.  The yield on the 1.375 percent bond due March 2020 was 1.23
percent, according to Gretai Securities Market. The Taiwan
dollar was at NT$31.765.  India: The Press Information Bureau will announce the
wholesale price index for food for the week ended Sept. 11. The
gauge rose 15.1 percent the week before.  The yield on the 7.80 percent bond due in May 2020 was 7.94
percent. The rupee was at 45.59.  To contact the reporter on this story:
